  <sec id="s0175" sec-type="supplementary-material">
    <title>Supplementary material</title>
    <p id="p0260">The following are the Supplementary data to this article:<supplementary-material content-type="local-data" id="m0095"><caption><title>Supplementary Figure S1</title><p><bold>Summary of three bulk RNA derived cell type references</bold>. Spearman's rank correlation analysis for each cell type by using the average expression for each gene in BlueprintEncode (<bold>A</bold>), DICE (<bold>B</bold>), &amp; MonacolImmune (<bold>C</bold>). UMAP dimension reduction analysis investigated the global landscape of cell type expression profiles in BlueprintEncode (<bold>D</bold>), DICE (<bold>E</bold>), &amp; MonacolImmune (<bold>F</bold>). Variance comparison of different gene features in BlueprintEncode (<bold>G</bold>), DICE (<bold>H</bold>), &amp; MonacolImmune (<bold>I</bold>). Each dot represents one gene feature. X-axis: type of gene feature (<italic>e.g.</italic>, protein coding, lincRNA). Y-axis: the variance of gene feature, scaled by absolute abundance. DICE, database of immune cell expression.</p></caption><media xlink:href="mmc1.pdf"/></supplementary-material></p>
    <p id="p0265">
      <supplementary-material content-type="local-data" id="m0090">
        <caption>
          <title>Supplementary Figure S2</title>
          <p><bold>Shared cell type-specific genes comparison between bulk-RNA and scRNA-seq derived references</bold>. Main CTGenes comparison between BlueprintEncode and DICE (<bold>A</bold>), BlueprintEncode and MonacoImmune (<bold>B</bold>), &amp; DICE and MonacoImmune (<bold>C</bold>). Fine CTGenes comparison between BlueprintEncode and DICE (<bold>D</bold>), BlueprintEncode and MonacoImmune (<bold>E</bold>), &amp; DICE and MonacoImmune (<bold>F</bold>). G. CTGenes comparison between BlueprintEncode and HCL. The number indicates the shared CTGenes number between two cell types.</p>
        </caption>
        <media xlink:href="mmc2.pdf"/>
      </supplementary-material>
    </p>
    <p id="p0270">
      <supplementary-material content-type="local-data" id="m0085">
        <caption>
          <title>Supplementary Figure S3</title>
          <p><bold>Overview of deCS flowchart for scRNA-seq annotation</bold>. We recommend users apply <italic>Seurat</italic> standard pre-processing workflow, including transcription noise cells cleaning, highly variable genes identification, dimension reduction, and cell clustering analysis. Then, <italic>Seurat</italic> FindAllMarkers() function can use to identify cluster-specific marker genes, and AverageExpression() function can use to calculate the gene average expression level for each cell cluster. Base on provided t-statistics and z-score for each gene, we implemented two test approaches for scRNA-seq cell type annotation. Strategy A: user can define genes with the highest <italic>t</italic>-statistics or <italic>z</italic>-score (top 5%) as CTGenes, then investigate whether a set of “cluster-specific marker genes” of interest are disproportionately overlapped with CTGenes by using Fisher’s exact test. Strategy B: user can calculate the PCC or SCC between query scaled expression profiles and <italic>t</italic>-statistics (or <italic>z</italic>-score) of each cell type in reference, then assigned the label with the highest score to query profile.</p>
        </caption>
        <media xlink:href="mmc3.pdf"/>
      </supplementary-material>
    </p>
